TWC WIOA Monthly Training Activity Report
Participant Name: Theodore Lawrence
Training Provider: Cloud Technology Experts
Training Program: Cloud/DevOps Engineering
Reporting Month: January 2026
Instructor: Dr. Damian Igbe, PhD
Submitted To: Ms. Crystal Norwood
________________________________________
Monthly Summary
During January 2026, training activities focused on advancing cloud infrastructure, Linux system administration, storage services, and networking fundamentals essential for cloud engineering and DevOps career pathways. Instruction emphasized hands-on implementation of AWS services including EC2, Route 53, Load Balancers, EBS storage, S3 static website hosting, and Virtual Private Cloud (VPC) architecture. Training sessions combined conceptual instruction, live troubleshooting, and real-world demonstrations using AWS cloud environments and Linux systems.
________________________________________
Weekly Activity Breakdown
________________________________________
Week of January 10, 2026
Training Activity Conducted
Training during this week focused on Linux package management and system administration using Ubuntu Linux. Instruction emphasized proper command syntax, troubleshooting common errors, and managing software through the Advanced Package Tool (APT).
Key skills and topics included:
• Updating package repositories and cache
• Installing and removing software packages
• Cleaning unused dependencies and cached files
• Listing installed packages and repositories
• Managing system services using systemctl
• Using grep and command piping for output filtering
• Understanding localhost and basic networking concepts
Hands-on demonstrations reinforced full package lifecycle management and service verification techniques.
________________________________________
Week of January 17, 2026
Training Activity Conducted
This week emphasized real-world AWS cloud infrastructure troubleshooting and secure service configuration. Students practiced diagnosing connectivity issues and configuring DNS and load balancing components.
Key skills and topics included:
• EC2 instance connectivity verification
• Route 53 hosted zone configuration and DNS records
• Application Load Balancer target group health analysis
• Domain routing to load balancers
• SSL/TLS certificate creation using AWS Certificate Manager
• Enabling HTTPS traffic for secure applications
• Systematic cloud troubleshooting methodologies
Live demonstrations showcased real production-style problem resolution scenarios.
________________________________________
Week of January 24, 2026
Training Activity Conducted
Training this week focused on AWS storage services, including Elastic Block Store (EBS) and Amazon S3 static website hosting. Instruction highlighted both Linux disk management and cloud-based object storage concepts.
Key skills and topics included:
• Creating and attaching EBS volumes to EC2 instances
• Identifying disks using lsblk
• Partitioning drives with fdisk
• Formatting file systems and mounting volumes
• Testing data persistence
• Configuring S3 buckets for static website hosting
• Applying bucket policies for public access
• Understanding snapshot backup concepts
Hands-on exercises reinforced secure storage management and cloud data durability.
________________________________________
Week of January 31, 2026
Training Activity Conducted
This week introduced foundational networking concepts and advanced AWS network architecture using Virtual Private Cloud (VPC).
Key skills and topics included:
• OSI Reference Model and TCP/IP communication process
• Data flow across network layers
• Understanding switches, routers, and network interfaces
• Creating AWS VPC environments from scratch
• CIDR block planning
• Public and private subnet creation
• Route table configuration
• Internet Gateway implementation
• Network isolation and security layering
Hands-on demonstrations validated connectivity and secure cloud network segmentation.
________________________________________
Overall Progress
Throughout January 2026, training activities significantly expanded practical cloud engineering and Linux system administration skills. The progression from package management to advanced cloud infrastructure, storage integration, troubleshooting, and network architecture strengthened real-world operational readiness. These competencies directly support career development in Cloud Operations, DevOps Engineering, and modern infrastructure management.

